ht|f|fp|1|at|Check back Stayman is one of the most useable conventions in modern bridge.

In this part of the movie I intend to introduce the convention and to show you a set of simple-to-apply responses.

The main purpose of the convention is to find eight-card fit in one of the major suits after opener 1NT or 2NT rebid.

It is easy to find a major fit when each partner has four cards in the same major suit. This process is simple – one bids 
the suit and the other shows support.

When opener holds five cards in a major suit and responder has three, any 5-major system allows recognizing the fit 
fast and easy.

The problem may occur when:
^b1.  Responder has five of his major and opener has only three. 
^b    In this case, after a No Trump bid by opener, responder may not rebid the suit with less than six cards. 
^b    As a consequence, the partnership will miss the 5-3 fit.

^b2. Opener has four hearts but he cannot introduce them after responder's 1@S due to a lack of strength for a reverse 
^b    bid. In this case, after a 1NT rebid by opener, responder may not rebid the suit with less than six cards. As a 
^b    consequence, the partnership will miss the 4-4 fit in those cases where responder has also four hearts.

The Check back Stayman  convention intends to solve the problem: the responder can use the unbid minor 
to ask opener about his majors holding. This bid is artificial and indicates nothing about responder's holding in the suit.|

