ht|f|cp|2|at|Two questions come up now:

1. What kind of hands responder describes by his artificial 2@C rebid?

2. How should opener go about responding to the 2!c bid?

Responder will usually hold:
1) Five cards in his major suit.
2) Eleven points or more.

With six cards in a major suit, responder may simply rebid his suit to set it as the trump suit.

Responder who holds less than eleven points, will preferably keep the contract as low as possible by passing the 
1NT rebid or rebidding his suit at the lowest level.

What do we want to achieve with the Check Back Stayman convention?
To look for a 4-4 fit in the unbid major.
To look for a 5-3 fit in responder's major.
 To get further information about opener's strength.

There are many variations and sub variations around in the bridge world, which I am unable to cover within a single article.

I will do my best to describe the system which is in my opinion easier to learn and to apply. 

However, I will give some references to other common alternatives during the course of describing the main line.|
