ht|b|fp|1|cp|2|at|^z4|

ht|f|cp|2|cs|1|at|PRIORITIES:

1. After {1@C  -  1@H, 1NT  -  2@C}: Or: {1@D  -  1@H, 1NT  -  2@C}

a. Opener bids 4-card spade suit (had he skipped the suit earlier).
b. Opener shows heart support with three hearts.
c. With none of the above, opener bids 2@D with 12-13 points and 2NT with 14 points.

2. After {1@C  -  1@S, 1NT  -  2@C}: Or: {1@D  -  1@S, 1NT  -  2@C}

a. Opener bids 4-card heart suit.
b. Opener shows spade support with three spades.
c. With none of the above, opener bids 2@D with 12-13 points and 2NT with 14 points.

By following these rules the partnership will most likely end up declaring the hand from the strong side and will help them 
to find the 4-4 fit, if there is such, rather than 5-3 fit. 

Many others prefer to show 3-card support first, while others prefer to show priority to their 4-card major first.

There are also many variations that don't make a distinction between minimum 1NT rebid (12-13 points) and maximum 
1NT rebid (14 points). Players who prefer this variation would always bid their major suit or show major support at the 
two level and deny the major fit by 2@D whether minimum or maximum. 

We have to distinct between two cases:
1. Responder's first bid was 1@H.
2. Responder's first bid was 1@S.|
