ht|f|fp|2|cs|1|at|{PART Two}|

ht|h|fp|1|cp|2|at|In the previous part I introduced the basic principles of the convention.

The second part will show some more useful ways to handle typical hands.

Look at the following hand:|


ht|m|cs|1|at|^o{|ih|psA763hK2dA5cAQ962|at|}|
ht|n|cs|1|at|^c{|ia|1cp1sp1Np?|at|}|

ht|t|fp|1|cp|2|at|East has 17 points together with a very good support for West's clubs.

West describes a 12-14 hand without spade support. 

Is there a chance for slam? 

There is not enough for 6NT which demands about 33 HCP, 
but 6@C might be a good spot.|
pg| ***** 53 ***** |


nt||

ht|e|fp|1|cs|1|at|^o{|ih|psA763hK2dA5cAQ962|at|}|
ht|f|cs|1|at|^c{|ia|1cp1sp1Np?|at|}|

ht|k|fp|1|cp|2|at|Many would bid 3@C, running the risk that partner will not get the correct message. Besides, 3@C should be considered as a limit bid and West can pass this!

4@C maybe? 4@C may be considered as Gerber. But even as a natural bid it takes too much bidding space. Moreover, if West holds only three clubs, it may be correct to stop at 3NT.

So it becomes clear that East has to find a way to show the club support while maintaining a chance to explore for the slam.

What East needs is a way to show the club support by using a forcing bid, simultaneously asking West to give 
additional information about his holding.| 

ht|u|cs|1|at|^n{|ia|1cp1sp1Np!2cp|at|}|
ht|u|fp|1|cp|2|at|The Check Back Stayman convention provides the tool:|
ht|z|fp|1|cp|2|at|After every response from West, East would be able to bid 3@C (or 4@C in case West jumps).|
pg| ***** 54 ***** |


nt||
ht|f|fp|1|cp|2|at|Following the above example, here is the rule: Check back Stayman followed by support for opener's first suit should be considered as a descriptive game forcing bid and slam invitation.| 

ht|h|fp|1|cp|2|at|Here is one more example to re illustrate the idea:|

ht|k|cs|1|at|^j{|ih|hsAJ3h83dAQJ97cT32|at|}^x{|ih|hsK4hAK952dKT85cA6|at|}|
ht|h|cs|1|at|^m{|ia|1dp1hp1Np!2cp2dp3dp3sp4Np5sp6dppp|at|}|
ht|p|fp|1|cp|2|at|2@C: Check Back Stayman, asking for three hearts.

3!D: Minimum, no three hearts.

3@D: Diamond support, game force, slam invitation.

3@S: Cue bid. After East's 3@D bid, West reevaluates his hand due to 
his strong 5-card suit and his controls and makes a move towards slam.

4NT: Roman keycard. 4@C was also available as a cue bid.

5@S: Two keycards and the @DQ.

The final 6@D contract is excellent. Notice that 6NT fails after a club lead.|
